abstract: PALM BEACH,. Fla., Jan. 31 -- The heat here for the last three or four-days has literally driven everybody into the sea. The temperature of the water yesterday was 78, and that of the air about two degrees higher. During the bathing hour the tennis courts are deserted. Golfers who have reached in their pilgrimage the hole called "the ocean" leave their clubs with caddies for a while and take a dip.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 3 -- The Panama Canal treaty has been reported to the Senate by the Committee on Foreign Relations. This was accomplished with the affirmative votes of all the members except Messrs. Bacon and Morgan. abstract: WASHINGTON Feb. 6 -- The two days' anti-trust debate in the House closed this evening with speeches by Mr. Littlefield and Mr. De Armond, the respective party leaders on the question. abstract: The development of rioting as an adjunct and accompaniment of the street car strike is an interesting phenomenon. In Montreal on the 5th inst. a meeting of street car employes was held. abstract: There is general dissatisfaction with conditions among the employes of the Manhattan Railroad Company, and it is said a strike may occur at any moment that will stop traffic on all the elevated lines. It is understood that motormen, engineers, firemen, guards, and "choppers" are interested in the movement, but that the porters and office men, who have organizations of their own, have not so far been invited to co-operate.

abstract: The Rev. Father Patrick R. abstract: ALBANY, Feb. 10 -- Gov. Odell left this city for Washington to-night, having been called there by President Roosevelt. He expects to spend three days at the National Capital. Lenahan, presented their side of the controversy and demanded consideration at the hands of the commission, claiming the legal right to earn a livelihood as they might elect, without the consent or dictation of the union.

abstract: ITHACA, N.Y., Feb. 11 -- President Schurman addressed the students of Cornell University to-day upon the typhoid lever epidemic now raging in Ithaca. He gave out that among the students there were to-day sixty-two cases receiving treatment in Ithaca, of which only seven were considered serious, while between 150 and 200 students have been sent to their homes by physicians upon the appearance of fever symptoms.

abstract: INDIANAPOLIS, Feb. 11 -- A bill authorizing baseball in cities was defeated in the State Senate to-day during an exciting session. It was really killed through the influence of the wife of Senator William H. O'Brien. Because of a pledge made to her he refused to vote when his name was called, and the total vote resulted 24 to 23.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 13 -- The last bill on the Administration's anti-trust programme, the Elkins Anti-Rebate bill, passed the House to-day after an hour's debate. This is all the discussion there has been of the measure, for the Senate did not debate it. abstract: Two young men faced each other in broad daylight yesterday in a duel with pistols in East Thirteenth Street, near Fourth Avenue. abstract: AMAGANSETT, N. Y., Feb. 15. -- Shouting "There she blows" on the beach early yesterday morning, "Nat" Edwards, a fisherman, directed attention to a big bull whale that was disporting a short distance off shore. abstract: WASHINGTON, N. J., Feb. 16. -- A headon collision occurred on the Lackawanna Railroad this morning about two miles this side of Phillipsburg. Three passengers were severely shaken up and were taken to Easton, Penn. Their names were not given out by the railroad employes. George Bowden, baggage master of one of the trains, was severely hurt, and it is believed his injuries will result fatally.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 16. -- The Senate today passed the Philippine Currency bill. The amendment offered by Mr. Patterson (Dem., Col.,) several days ago, providing for a conference between gold and silver standard countries to fix a commercial exchange, was agreed to without division. abstract: To the Editor of The New York Times: I have read with considerable interest the speech of Senator Tillman delivered at the Press Club dinner. abstract: It is a fact not generally known that the ambulance service in Paris is the poorest of any city in Western Europe. The calls for ambulances are usually sent out from Prefecture of Police, and hence a case must first be reported before a call can be made. The police very often press passing vehicles into service, as experience has taught them that it may be three hours before the arrival of an ambulance.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 22 -- The quaint old town of Alexandria, Va., will celebrate Washington's Birthday to-morrow with more than usual enthusiasm. Before the war the citizens used to make the day one of the reddest of the year, but of late they have rather neglected it. This year a general feeling of loyalty to the Father of his Country has swept over the community and there will be a grand turnout.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 22 -- It is generally believed that the decision of the United States Supreme Court in the lottery cases will tie handed down to-morrow. abstract: The London Lancet announces a discovery which may be found to have great pathological interest. abstract: WILLIAMSPORT, Penn., Feb. 26 -- It has become known here that plans are on foot for a railroad across Pennsylvania, which, it is said, is to connect the Wabash system and the Ontario and Western, giving the former road an outlet to tidewater and eventually letting it into New York. abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 27 -- Announcement was made at to-day's session of the congress of the Daughters of the American Revolution of the result of the vote for officers last night. It was found that Mrs. James R. Melon of Pennsylvania and Mrs. M.S. Lockwood of the District of Columbia were tied in the vote on Vice President, and one must be chosen later.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 27 -- There was a prolonged and sharp discussion in the Senate Inter-State Commerce Committee over what is known as the Hepburn package amendment to the Inter-State Commerce act. This bill makes all packages of goods shipped from one State to another subject in transit to the laws of the State into which they are shipped.

abstract: Policeman M.J. Coyne of the Delancey Street Station jumped into the East River at Corlears Street last night to rescue John Harkins, a homeless man, who had fallen in. Both were swept over to the navy yard by the swift current, Coyne all the time holding Harkins. They were finally rescued by two policemen who had put out after them in a boat.
